    value: 죄를 사면해 주어 소환하는 것.
english:
  title: Record of the Righteous Granary and Official Residence of Qinghe County
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the winter of jiǎsi, I was exiled to Ninghai. The following spring, I was transferred to Xinghai. Traveling southward along the coast, I passed through the territory known as Qinghe. At that time, due to Japanese pirates, the coastal lands had become wild tangles of bramble and thorn. Though Ninghai and Xinghai had only recently been fortified—scarcely a year or two—a few survivors had returned to their livelihood. But places like Qinghe remained desolate and empty. After my pardon and recall, I heard that Qinghe too had been fortified to gather its wandering people.

    This summer, Music Master Kim came bearing a poem, composed by the Yellow Oriole, Minister Lee—a work on the Righteous Granary and Official Residence of Qinghe. It praised in considerable detail the administrative achievements of our magistrate Min. On water, battle vessels were stationed; on land, garrison posts were established—the defenses against invasion were complete. The dispersed had returned, the fields were tilled, wells were dug—the people found peace. Thus was the art of nurturing the people perfected. A righteous granary was established to benefit the poor. An official residence was built to receive traveling officials. Every duty of a magistrate was fulfilled. Reading this poem, one can imagine the character of the man himself.

    I reflected with admiration: All things rise and fall according to their appointed seasons. When decline reaches its limit, prosperity must return—such is the natural order. The border lands have long known turmoil and displacement. Now, in this auspicious age when the Dragon Throne has risen to power, the old is reformed and the new established. The sea pirates are subdued and fearful, the frontier is at peace. Worthy administrators have been selected to govern the people, transforming yesterday's wilderness of thorns into fertile fields of mulberry and hemp. The time of return to prosperity has come at precisely this moment—fortune indeed for these people. And the righteous granary, above all, serves the people well: in abundance, we gather; in scarcity, we distribute. Though famine may come, the people need not starve. This is truly a good system. Magistrate Min pursues it diligently. May those who succeed him preserve it without letting it fall into neglect. Then shall we see the people grow prosperous and flourish, achieving a realm of longevity. This is no mere dream.

    I myself have walked those lands and witnessed their desolation. The sorrow I felt then has never left my heart. Now, seeing this poem, how can I not rejoice for the people of Qinghe? Music Master Kim requested that I write this account. Thus I commit these words to paper.

    Magistrate Min's name is Tianzuo, and he is of Yeongju. Though I have not met him personally, Music Master Kim is pure and diligent, and the Yellow Oriole is noble and cautious—neither given to careless praise or blame. Therefore, I can trust in Magistrate Min's character.

    Written on the sixteenth day of the fifth month, in the thirty-second year of the Hongwu era.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Jiǎsi year: This refers to 1389 (己巳) in the Hongwu calendar of the Ming Dynasty'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Ninghai and Xinghai: Coastal regions in what is now Gyeongsangbuk-do, Korea, suffering greatly from Japanese pirate raids during this period'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The pardon and recall (賜環): Gwon Geun was actually imprisoned and later amnestied and restored to office—this is likely what is referenced here'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Yellow Oriole, Minister Lee (黃鸝李公): A poetic name for a colleague who composed the poem praising Magistrate Min'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Righteous Granary (義倉): A public grain storage system designed to provide relief during times of famine—an important institution in East Asian governance'
